<h2>Understanding PDF Passwords: User vs. Owner</h2>

<p>PDFs can have two distinct types of password protection:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>User password (open password):</strong> Prevents anyone from opening the file without entering the password. If you have this password, you can unlock the file using the tool above.</li>
  <li><strong>Owner password (permissions password):</strong> Allows the file to be opened but restricts actions like printing, copying text, or editing. You may be able to open and read the file but not print it.</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Some PDFs have both types set. The PDFWonder tool handles both — enter either the user or owner password to remove it.
</p>

<h2>How to Unlock a PDF on Windows</h2>

<p>On Windows, there is no built-in tool specifically for removing PDF passwords. Your options:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Browser tool (recommended):</strong> Use the <a href="/pdfwonder/pdf-unlock">PDFWonder PDF Unlocker</a> in any browser — no installation needed.</li>
  <li><strong>Adobe Acrobat (paid):</strong> Open the PDF in Acrobat → File → Properties → Security → change the Security Method to "No Security" → save.</li>
  <li><strong>Google Chrome print trick:</strong> Open the PDF in Chrome (enter the password when prompted) → press Ctrl+P → choose "Save as PDF" as the printer → click Save. This sometimes saves without the password, but only works for owner-password restrictions, not user passwords.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to Unlock a PDF on Mac</h2>

<p>Mac's <strong>Preview app</strong> can save a PDF without its password:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in Preview and enter the password when prompted.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>File → Export as PDF…</strong></li>
  <li>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</li>
</ol>

<p>
  Preview exports the PDF without encryption. This works for most user-password-protected PDFs. If Preview still asks for a password when you reopen the exported file, use the browser tool above.
</p>

<h2>How to Remove PDF Password on iPhone or Android</h2>

<p>On mobile, the browser-based tool works directly in Safari or Chrome:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Open <a href="/pdfwonder/pdf-unlock">PDFWonder PDF Unlocker</a> in your mobile browser.</li>
  <li>Tap the upload area and select the PDF from your Files app (iOS) or storage (Android).</li>
  <li>Enter the password and tap Remove Password &amp; Download.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Is It Legal to Unlock a PDF?</h2>

<p>
  Removing a password from a PDF you own, or have the right to access, is entirely legal. Common legitimate reasons include:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>You set the password yourself and want to remove it</li>
  <li>A client sent you a document you are authorised to edit</li>
  <li>You want to archive the file without repeatedly entering a password</li>
</ul>
<p>
  It is not legal to unlock PDFs you do not have permission to access, such as copyrighted ebooks or confidential files belonging to others.
</p>

<h2>Why Remove a PDF Password? Common Reasons</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Convenience:</strong> Stop typing the same password every time you open a regularly-used document</li>
  <li><strong>Printing:</strong> Some PDFs with owner passwords block printing — removing the password enables printing</li>
  <li><strong>Sharing:</strong> Share a document with a colleague without them needing the password</li>
  <li><strong>Merging:</strong> PDF merger tools often cannot combine encrypted PDFs — unlock them first</li>
  <li><strong>Archiving:</strong> Remove passwords before archiving files to avoid lockout if the password is forgotten</li>
</ul>

